            <h3>Computers, printers, and scanners</h3>
            <p>All libraries in Kotka offer computers that can be used without reservation. You can also borrow a laptop to use on-site.</p> 
            <p>Copying and printing are available at all libraries.</p>
            
            <p><a href="https://kyyti.finna.fi/themes/custom/files/kirjastotulostus_kotka.pdf">Instructions for printing, copying, and scanning</a></p>
            
            <h3>Tablets</h3>
            <p>The main library offers Hublet tablets for customer use. You can borrow a Hublet for two hours from the second-floor kiosk using your library card and a four-digit PIN. The devices work on-site and allow you to check emails, browse the web, use social media, play games, listen to music, watch videos, read e-newspapers, and access other digital library materials and services.</p>
            <p>Hublet usage is secure because all browsing data and information stored on the device is automatically erased when you return the device to the charging station.</p>
            <p>In the Karhula and Karhuvuori libraries, you can borrow iPad tablets for in-library use from customer service.</p>
            
            <h3>Wireless network</h3>
            <p>All Kotka libraries provide free wireless internet.</p>
            <ul class="list-bullets">
                <li>Network name: kirjasto-vierailija</li>
                <li>Password: kirjasto</li>
            </ul>
    
            <h3>3D printers</h3>
            <p>The main library’s 3D printers allow you to create physical objects from non-toxic and biodegradable PLA plastic. Printing is free.</p>
            <p>If 3D printing is new to you, the staff will guide you in choosing a model, printing it, and discussing further printing possibilities. 
            For your first print, you might create a keychain, a small figurine, a name tag, or explore other models together with the staff.</p>
            
            <p>You can also print your own models. The model file must be in either STL or OBJ format.
            Prior to printing, the model file is converted on the library computer into a format the 3D printer understands.</p>
            <p>Devices: two Prenta Duo XL SE printers and Simplify3D slicing software.</p>
            
